Histogramms¶

A histogramm displays the intensity distribution of an image.

  • https://docs.opencv.org/master/d1/db7/tutorial_py_histogram_begins.html
  • https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/opencv-python-program-analyze-image-using-histogram/

Gradient Masks¶

Last week we used black and white masks for blending images. This week, we will be using a grayscale mask for blending.

In [1]:
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
import cv2

blend1 = cv2.imread('blend1.jpg')
blend2 = cv2.imread('blend2.jpg')
mask =  cv2.imread('blend-mask.jpg')
plt.imshow(cv2.cvtColor(mask, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB))
plt.show()

# Convert mask to be floats (range 0.0 to 1.0)
mask = mask / 255

# Blend the two images together
new_image = blend1 * mask + blend2 * (1 - mask)
new_image = new_image.astype(np.uint8)
plt.imshow(cv2.cvtColor(new_image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB))
plt.show()

Thresholds¶

Threshold images are used to create black-white masks.

  • https://docs.opencv.org/master/d7/d4d/tutorial_py_thresholding.html
  • image segmentation
In [3]:
mask = cv2.imread('blend-mask2.jpg')
print('Gradient Mask')
plt.imshow(cv2.cvtColor(mask, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB))
plt.show()

print('Threshold - 127')
ret,thresh1 = cv2.threshold(mask, 127, 255, cv2.THRESH_BINARY)
plt.imshow(cv2.cvtColor(thresh1, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB))
plt.show()

print('Threshold - 200')
ret,thresh1 = cv2.threshold(mask, 200, 255, cv2.THRESH_BINARY)
plt.imshow(cv2.cvtColor(thresh1, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB))
plt.show()

Threshold - 127

Threshold - 200

Kernels¶

A kernel is a small matrix that is applied on an image. They allow you to blur, sharpen, noise reduction, edge detection. This process is called "convolution".

Please watch the following video:

Video on convolution Kernel

  • image_processing)
  • http://setosa.io/ev/image-kernels/
  • https://docs.opencv.org/3.4/d5/d69/tutorial_py_non_local_means.html
In [4]:
image = cv2.imread('noise1.jpg')
print('Original noisy image')
plt.imshow(cv2.cvtColor(image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB))
plt.show()

blur = cv2.GaussianBlur(image, (3, 3), 0)
print('Gaussian Blur image')
plt.imshow(cv2.cvtColor(blur, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB))
plt.show()

print('Mean Kernel image')
kernel = np.ones((3,3),np.float32)/9
blur2 = cv2.filter2D(image,-1,kernel)
plt.imshow(cv2.cvtColor(blur2, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB))
plt.show()

median = cv2.medianBlur(image,5)
print('medianBlur() image')
plt.imshow(cv2.cvtColor(median, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB))
plt.show()

Original noisy image

Gaussian Blur image

Mean Kernel image

medianBlur() image

Here is an example of using blur to create a smooth mask¶

In [5]:
blend1 = cv2.imread('blend1.jpg')
blend2 = cv2.imread('blend2.jpg')

rows, cols, ch = blend1.shape

mask = np.zeros((rows, cols, ch), dtype=np.uint8)
cv2.circle(mask, (cols // 2, rows // 2), 200, (255, 255, 255), -1)
print('Mask with simple circle')
plt.imshow(cv2.cvtColor(mask, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB))
plt.show()

# smooth mask with a blur a few times
for i in range(100):
    mask = cv2.GaussianBlur(mask, (35, 35), 0)
print('Mask with blurred circle')
plt.imshow(cv2.cvtColor(mask, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB))
plt.show()

# Convert mask to be floats (range 0.0 to 1.0)
mask = mask / 255

# Blend the two images together
new_image = blend1 * mask + blend2 * (1 - mask)
new_image = new_image.astype(np.uint8)
print('Blended image')
plt.imshow(cv2.cvtColor(new_image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB))
plt.show()

Mask with simple circle

Mask with blurred circle

Blended image
